What if we only wanted to know what the last digit will be? Is there a shortcut? Keep reading to find out, or skip ahead to the challenge if you think you already know.

Let's see what happens if we start multiplying these numbers out in order:

We could keep going, but there's already a zero in the last place. No matter what number we multiply by any multiple of ten, we'll always end up with another multiple of ten. The final product will have a zero in the ones place (((by the way, the product happens to be 362,880).362,880).362,880).

Did we have to go through the remaining four multiplications to figure this out, though? Not if we remembered that multiplication is associative. We can move and regroup the numbers we're multiplying however we want:

Since we have a 222 and a 555 in the product, we know the product is a multiple of 2×5=10.2 \times 5 = 10.2×5=10. Without doing a single calculation, we can conclude that the last digit will be a zero.

Happy July, everyone!

Our problem is 1 x 3 x 5 x 7 x 9 x 11 x 13. Given this, we have a five.

Remember that anything times five ends with five or zero. We do not have 0 as a choice, but here is why it is five:

5 x 1 = 5 5 x 2 = 10 5 x 3 = 15 5 x 4 = 20 5 x 5 = 25

And so forth. Notice that the end number alternates between 5s and 0s. 5 times any even number gives a 0, and an odd gives a 5.

To see why, we must remember this rule: odd times odd equals odd. We have all odd numbers, so the product must be odd. 5 x odd gives 5 as an end number (the final result is 135,135).

I hope this helps!

This is because all even numbers are a multiple of two. 2 x 5 = 10, so all of those will end in a 0. On the other hand, if you multiply 5 by an odd number, you have a 5 at the end. All odd numbers are an even number - 1. So when you multiply by an odd number, you can take it as (even number x 5) + (-1 x 5). -1 x 5 is -5. A multiply of ten minus 5 ends with 5!

Every even number can be expressed as 2×n2 \times n2×n and every odd number can be expressed as 2×m+12 \times m + 12×m+1 for some integers nnn and mmm.

Let's see what happens when we multiply with 5: 5×(2×n)=10×n 5 \times (2 \times n) = 10 \times n 5×(2×n)=10×n 5×(2×m+1)=10×m+5 5 \times (2 \times m + 1) = 10 \times m + 5 5×(2×m+1)=10×m+5 Since multiples of 10 always end on 000, we see that 555 times an even number ends on 000 and 555 times an odd number ends on 0+5=50+5=50+5=5.

In the question, we only have odd numbers, so the product will end on a 555.
